choices.text: the Ebola outbreak. The outbreak started in Guinea in December 2013 and spread to Liberia and Sierra Leone. The outbreak was declared over in June 2016. The outbreak was the largest in history, with 28,616 cases and 11,310 deaths reported in Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone. The outbreak was caused by the Ebola virus, which is a rare but deadly virus that is transmitted through direct contact with the blood or bodily fluids of an infected person. The virus can also be transmitted through contact with contaminated objects, such as needles or syringes. The symptoms of Ebola include fever, headache, joint and muscle aches, sore throat, and weakness, followed by diarrhea, vomiting, and stomach pain. A rash, red eyes, and internal and external bleeding may occur later on. There is no specific treatment for Ebola, but supportive care can help patients survive the infection.
